Introduction

Remember our metaphors the one where we consider our network a building? The things that we are going to talk about involves virtual networks so similar to vlans they are networks but theyre like that in a logical sense, its mostly software defined stuff but admittedly they can and do have real connectivity but within private networks so if you connect your stuff to azure it's with a vpn or ExpressRoute(if your company is loaded). VNets are mainly for securing communications with their resources there, also scalability and availability. Scalability means that if you need more of a said resource you can expand current capacity or acquire more instances of that resource to accommodate your needs. Availability means even if hell freezes over, your services and operations are still running no matter what. 

Plan Virtual Networks

Earlier i mentioned things about network segmentation and why does the concept exist in the first place. Those principles perfectly apply to how we want to plan our networks here. Planning makes sure you don't over or under allocate addresses within your virtual network. It totally depends on your use cases whether you're just planning a small scale project or a huge cloud server. You can either create a dedicated private cloud-only virtual network(fancy way of saying you can literally prop up a cloud server), securely extend your data center with virtual networks(so if you want to connect your on premises stuff to the cloud you can do it but for the sole reason to extend capacity) or enable hybrid cloud scenarios(just the same as the second point but your intent is to facilitate certain stuff on prem and then in the cloud). So to tie back to our metaphors, this is how Azure, a construction company wants to give you the opportunity to have your own personal building somewhere far away, they're in charge of everything except whats the layout of the building and the rooms sectioned off and the objects within those rooms and how is the floor plan structured. 

Create Subnets

I've already talked about the stuff you would mostly need in the previous sections however i do want to add a few key considerations. You should consider service requirements. Every resource has their own network requirements in the building created by Azure and the types of data coming and going from these services. A service like an azure firewall, will definitely need their own dedicated subnet so they can function properly. Consider your network virtual appliances, as we go over more advanced stuff within this guide we have to consider that Azure naturally routes network traffic between all subnets in a network. That's a huge no no when it comes to security, but we can override the settings wherever it applies accordingly. Consider also your network security groups because they act as your firewalls, allowing or not allowing certain ip ranges and whatnot. 

Create Virtual Networks

These are pretty straightforward and so easy yet dry i dont even know what to commentate on so here you go:

When you create a virtual network, you need to define the IP address space for the network.

Plan to use an IP address space that's not already in use in your organization.

The address space for the virtual network can be either on-premises or in the cloud, but not both.

To create a virtual network, you need to define at least one subnet.

Each subnet contains a range of IP addresses that fall within the virtual network address space.

The address range for each subnet must be unique within the address space for the virtual network.

The range for one subnet can't overlap with other subnet IP address ranges in the same virtual network.

You can create a virtual network in the Azure portal. Provide the Azure subscription, resource group, virtual network name, and service region for the network.

